Do you have a tendency to put your fitness and nutrition in a separate world from your ACTUAL life? 

Here’s an example: 
You *want* to do Dry January but your birthday is at the end of the month. 

When you think about celebrating your birthday, you want a cocktail or a glass of wine—pretty reasonable if you ask me. 

Before I keep going, don’t get me wrong on bashing Dry January: I get the intention—you recognize that alcohol is LIMITING you from reaching your goals:
❌ it causes shitty sleep and poor recovery
❌ it lowers your inhibition, which in many of my clients’ cases, leads to poor food choices
❌ it limits your performance in the gym the next day—if you even make it there at all.

BUT, alcohol is social. There’s an aspect to it that surrounds CELEBRATION. 

If you want a drink specifically on YOUR BIRTHDAY, it’s not about the alcohol itself: it’s the fact that it represents celebrating. 

So really, what we’re questioning is 
your relationship TO alcohol. And here’s my hot take:

Cutting it out for a month probably won’t improve the relationship. It’s same principle as to why restrictive diets don’t work…

If you’re doing Dry January because you’re curious about sobriety and plan to continue beyond the month, again, that’s different—and good on YOU. 

Personally, I look for the behaviors that create the BIGGEST CHANGE because they’ll move the needles the most for me. Dry January doesn’t change my lifestyle because I don’t drink THAT frequently. 

So maybe my bias is just showing in this post. 

Would love more thoughts on this one. Anyone out there see a lot of success with Dry January long term? Prove me wrong👇🏻👇🏻

A client commented to me the other day—“I don’t know how you find time to manage YOUR nutrition amid all that you do.” And my initial reaction? I laughed. 

Because…
I often don’t manage it to the *degree* that I know I can. 

BUT that doesn’t upset me—and that’s come from growth in the process for sure—but it’s also come from a few things that YOU can adopt RIGHT NOW, literally today. 

Why? Because it comes from making the “seemingly small stuff,” your foundation, your list of non-negotiables. 

Here are mine:
✅ Get as much quality protein where you can [this is harder when traveling so why I put it first with this video]
✅ Understand + consider how your breakfast decision impacts lunch, and how lunch impacts dinner. Nothing happens in a vacuum—one meal decision should ALWAYS influence the next
✅ You CAN have ANYTHING, just not everything [especially not at the same time—see above 😈]
✅ Get some kind of daily movement because yes, even a 20 minute walk is better than missing your lift entirely

And the last one? If the above doesn’t happen at least 5-6 days out of the week? It’s okay—the only consequence is that we SHIFT THE TIMELINE on OUR GOALS: 

🚨 This one is important: I think it’s the one that not enough people do and it leads to the most disappointment. It leads to the assumption that what you’re trying to do to lose weight, “isn’t working.” 

Have you given it enough time? Are you adjusting the game plan? More context on that one in our latest podcast episode for @thefyx.officialpod, too 😉

What non-negotiables are you committing to? Hint: start SMALL, start with what you can GUARANTEE. Tell me some in the comments to get this Monday started right ♥️ 👇🏻

It’s actually not that complicated—it’s about how you show up, REGULARLY.

You wanna know why it feels complicated?
Because of the diet approach that tried to market itself to you as *simpler* than the basics. It only seems simpler because they’re telling you that you don’t HAVE to do it for as long… 

“Because 30 days is all you need to see results…” 

But are those results LIFELONG?
If the BEHAVIORS aren’t lifelong, the results won’t be.

These are 5 behaviors that I think you CAN commit to FOREVER—forever, ever. Will you got them perfectly, every single day? Nah, probably not. 

But most of the time is better than none of the time. And the restrictive diets almost always lead to none of the time. Think about it.. 

What sounds better and easier? A low carb, low fat, low calorie world of saying no to what you really WANT OR saying yes to… 

dinner plans on a Friday night
a glass of wine 🍷 or your 🍕 from your favorite Italian spot
A 30 min strength training workout instead of an hour plus on the treadmill

You’re doing this for life either way. So if you committed to a plan in the month of January and you keep on keepin’ on into February, I hope you can say the same in May and June and July… and 2024…

Selfishness—a word that makes a lot of people cringe, especially women [at least I think so]. But listen to this whole clip and try to tell me that it DOESN’T flip your definition of “being selfish” completely on its head.   In today’s episode of @thefyx.officialpod, we chopped it up with @michaelchernow, Founder of @kreaturesofhabit on all things morning routine, sleep, fear, habits, and the power of your decisions. 

Michael’s got a next level morning routine. 

And sure, it was cool to hear about the different activities he stacks up to set his day up for success.
